  "prompt": "Can some one help me with a daily routine for CAT 2016?",
  "response": "Okay, let's craft a daily routine to help you prepare effectively for CAT 2016.  Keep in mind that this is a general template. You'll need to personalize it based on your:\n\n*   **Current Proficiency:**  Where are you strongest and weakest in VARC, DILR, and QA?\n*   **Time Availability:** How many hours can you realistically dedicate each day?\n*   **Learning Style:** Do you learn best through reading, practice, or a combination?\n*   **Personal Schedule:**  Consider your work, college, family, and other commitments.\n*   **Target Score:** The kind of B-school you are aiming for.\n\n**Key Principles to Remember:**\n\n*   **Consistency is King:**  A little bit every day is far more effective than cramming occasionally.\n*   **Quality over Quantity:** Focus on understanding concepts deeply, not just rushing through problems.\n*   **Strategic Weakness Tackling:** Prioritize improving your weak areas, but don't neglect your strengths.\n*   **Regular Mock Tests:** Simulate the CAT environment to build test-taking stamina and strategy.\n*   **Rest and Recharge:** Don't burn out. Adequate sleep and downtime are crucial for performance.\n\n**Here's a Sample Daily Routine (Adapt to Your Needs):**\n\n**Time Slot** | **Activity** | **Focus** | **Notes**\n------- | -------- | -------- | --------\n**Morning (7:00 AM - 9:00 AM)** | **VARC (Verbal Ability & Reading Comprehension)** | Concept Building / Practice | *   **30 mins:** Read newspaper editorials (The Hindu, Economic Times) or articles on diverse topics (Aeon, Arts & Letters Daily) for vocabulary building and comprehension. *   **60 mins:** Solve Reading Comprehension passages and Verbal Ability questions (Para jumbles, Odd One Out, Summary). *   **30 mins:** Review answers and analyze mistakes. Identify patterns in errors and revise relevant concepts.\n**Mid-day (12:00 PM - 2:00 PM)** | **DILR (Data Interpretation & Logical Reasoning)** | Concept building / Practice | *   **30 mins:** Learn concepts related to DI (graphs, tables, charts) and LR (arrangements, selections, networks). *   **60 mins:** Solve 2-3 DI sets and 2-3 LR sets of varying difficulty. *   **30 mins:** Analyze solutions, understand different approaches, and identify areas for improvement. Focus on time management.\n**Evening (6:00 PM - 8:00 PM)** | **QA (Quantitative Ability)** | Concept Building / Practice | *   **30 mins:** Revise formulas, theorems, and concepts from a specific QA topic (e.g., Arithmetic, Algebra, Geometry). *   **60 mins:** Solve problems related to the chosen topic. Start with easier questions and gradually increase the difficulty level. *   **30 mins:** Review solutions, identify alternative methods, and address any conceptual gaps.\n**Night (9:00 PM - 10:00 PM)** | **Review & Relaxation** | Consolidation & Rest | *   **30 mins:** Review the day's learning. Make notes of key concepts, formulas, and problem-solving strategies. *   **30 mins:** Relax, read a book (not CAT-related), listen to music, or spend time with family.  Avoid screens right before bed.\n\n**Weekend Schedule (Example):**\n\n*   **Saturday:**\n    *   Follow the weekday routine.\n    *   Take a full-length mock test (3 hours).\n    *   Spend 2-3 hours analyzing the mock test, identifying strengths and weaknesses.\n\n*   **Sunday:**\n    *   Focus on revising weak areas identified from the mock test.\n    *   Solve additional problems related to those topics.\n    *   Relax and recharge.\n\n**Important Considerations & Tips:**\n\n*   **Prioritize Weak Areas:**  If you're weak in QA, dedicate more time to it than to VARC if you're already strong there. Use diagnostic tests to pinpoint your weaknesses.\n*   **Use Quality Resources:**  Refer to reputable CAT preparation books, online resources, and coaching materials.  Consider Arun Sharma's books, or online portals like 2IIM or CrackU.\n*   **Join Study Groups (Optional):**  Discuss concepts and problem-solving approaches with fellow aspirants.\n*   **Mock Test Analysis is Crucial:** Don't just take mock tests; analyze them thoroughly.  Identify:\n    *   Types of questions you consistently get wrong.\n    *   Topics where you're slow.\n    *   Silly mistakes you're making.\n    *   Your time management strategy.\n*   **Time Management Strategies:** Practice techniques like:\n    *   **The 15-Minute Rule:** If you can't solve a question in 15 minutes, skip it and come back later.\n    *   **Sectional Time Limits:** Stick to the allotted time for each section.\n    *   **Prioritizing Easy Questions:**  Solve the easier questions first to maximize your score.\n*   **Stay Motivated:**  Set realistic goals, track your progress, and reward yourself for achieving milestones.\n*   **Health is Wealth:**  Maintain a healthy diet, exercise regularly, and get enough sleep.  Stress can significantly impact performance.\n*   **Adapt and Adjust:**  Continuously evaluate your routine and adjust it based on your progress and needs.\n\n**Breaking Down Sections:**\n\n*   **VARC:**\n    *   **Reading Comprehension:**  Practice reading different types of passages (abstract, scientific, literary).  Focus on understanding the main idea, tone, and author's perspective. Improve reading speed.\n    *   **Verbal Ability:**  Master grammar rules, vocabulary, and logical reasoning skills. Practice para jumbles, odd one out, and summary questions.\n*   **DILR:**\n    *   **Data Interpretation:**  Be comfortable with different types of graphs and charts. Practice data analysis and interpretation skills.\n    *   **Logical Reasoning:**  Develop strong analytical and problem-solving skills. Practice different types of reasoning questions (arrangements, selections, networks, coding-decoding).\n*   **QA:**\n    *   **Arithmetic:**  Master topics like percentages, ratios, averages, profit and loss, time and work, and simple and compound interest.\n    *   **Algebra:**  Practice topics like equations, inequalities, functions, and logarithms.\n    *   **Geometry:**  Revise formulas and theorems related to lines, angles, triangles, circles, and solid geometry.\n    *   **Modern Math:**  Learn concepts of permutations and combinations, probability, and set theory.\n\n**Final Thoughts:**\n\nSuccess in CAT requires a well-structured study plan, consistent effort, and a positive attitude. Good luck with your preparation! Remember to personalize this routine and stick to it as much as possible. Let me know if you have specific areas you'd like me to elaborate on!\n",
